The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Business Briefs
                              
	 New Delhi, Dec. 24: The National Pharmaceutical Pricing Authority (NPPA) has raised prices of six drugs, including anti-asthmatic and pain killers, chairman S.M. Jharwal said. The NPPA has also cut prices of 29 other drugs after reviewing prices of 59 formulations for treating diabetes, allergy, asthma and pain killers. Eli Lilly, Pfizer, Novartis, Sanofi Aventis, GSK, Aventis Pharma and Cipla will be affected by the price revision.                            
	 New Delhi, Dec. 24: Telecom operators added 18.98 million mobile subscribers in October, taking the total number of telephone users in the country to 742.12 million, sectoral regulator Trai said. With this, teledensity (telephones per 100 people) in India touched 62.51 per cent.                            
	 New Delhi, Dec. 24: A parliamentary panel has questioned top officials of the civil aviation ministry and demanded quick action to curb overpricing of air tickets. Members of the committee on estimates expressed concern over the steep rise in fares and wondered whether anybody had control over selling tickets.                            
	 Tokyo, Dec. 24: Mitsubishi Motors will start selling Suzukis new Solio compact cars under its own brand next year to boost sales in the shrinking Japan market, the two companies said. It is the first time the two car makers have struck such a deal for the domestic market.                            
	 Mumbai, Dec. 24: Standard Chartered today increased its base rate by 50 basis points to 8 per cent and deposit rates by up to 75 basis points for medium-term maturities, effective December 21.                            
	 Indore, Dec. 24: The Tata group is planning to increase its budget hotels to over 70 from 25 in the next few years.                            
	 Mumbai, Dec. 24: Aditya Birla Retail is eyeing a breakeven at the company level by 2014-15. The retail major is also looking at scaling up its supermarket and hypermarket chain to 1,300 and 65, respectively, by 2016.                                                                                                                          
